Imagine a very long webpage with many sections (like an HTML specification on a single page). If the user requests a specific section (e.g., page.html#section7), how would it be if the web server first streams this section and then the others?
Stream order:
1. Beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for Section 7
3. HTML for Section 1, 2, 3, etc.
Then the browser would ensure that sections 1 through 6 are displayed *above* section 7 on the webpage.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to reimplement elements with JavaScript. I simply want to have an extra long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed that way, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would not be streamed sequentially, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed sequentially.
@user22 You can also rearrange documents without using JavaScript. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to perform an action, but you can use query string search parameters so the server knows which section you want first. When reordering the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML feature that allows content not to be streamed in sequence, but for the browser to arrange the content in the DOM order.
But the idea with the slots looks promising. I'll try that.
@user22 oh, do you want the browser to fix the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first, so that the user can see it as quickly as possible. If that were possible without affecting the DOM order, that would be great, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
Therefore, section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should appear as if all sections had been streamed in sequence.
@user22 @user23 Take a look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
